---

<section id="methodology" class="py-16 border-t border-border">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 space-y-12">

    <!-- Opening -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-foreground">How This Works</h2>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Every transit equity debate comes down to a definition nobody agrees on: what counts as
        "good service." A bus every 10 minutes? Every 15? Within a 5-minute walk, or a 10-minute
        walk? These thresholds determine which neighborhoods look well-served and which look
        underserved, and the choice is usually buried in a methodology appendix, invisible
        to the people arguing about the results.
      </p>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        This tool makes that invisible choice visible.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- What the Map Shows -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-foreground">What the Map Shows</h3>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        The map displays San Francisco's 41 Analysis Neighborhoods, each colored by what
        percentage of residents have good transit access, using whatever definition of
        "good" you choose.
      </p>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Two sliders control the definition:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        <li>
          <strong>Frequency:</strong> "A bus every ___ minutes or better" (4 to 20 minutes)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Walking time:</strong> "Within a ___ minute walk" (3 to 15 minutes)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        As you drag, the map recolors and the headline number updates. Drag the frequency
        slider from 10 minutes to 15 and watch a neighborhood flip color. That change
        reflects a different policy position, not different data.
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-3 rounded-xl bg-muted/50 p-4 text-sm text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          <strong>Time of day:</strong> Service varies throughout the day. A selector
          lets you switch between five time windows: AM Rush (6&ndash;9 AM),
          Midday (9 AM&ndash;3 PM), PM Rush (3&ndash;7 PM),
          Evening (7 PM&ndash;Midnight), and Overnight (Midnight&ndash;6 AM).
          The map updates to show access during each window.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Route mode:</strong> By default, the tool counts all buses arriving
          at a stop together. If three lines each run every 20 minutes, the combined frequency
          is roughly every 7 minutes. But if you need a specific line, your actual wait is
          20 minutes. A toggle switches between "All buses" (combined frequency) and
          "Your route" (single-route headway), so you can see both perspectives.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Detail level:</strong> A Summary/Detailed toggle switches between
          neighborhood-level coloring and a finer-grained hexagonal grid that reveals variation
          <em>within</em> neighborhoods. For example, the east side of the Sunset near the
          L-Taraval is better served than the western blocks.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Data Sources -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-foreground">Data Sources</h3>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        All data used in this tool is public and free. Every dataset is linked so you can
        verify the inputs yourself.
      </p>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-border text-left">
              <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-foreground">Data</th>
              <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-foreground">Source</th>
              <th class="py-2 font-medium text-foreground">What it provides</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-muted-foreground">
            <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">Residential addresses</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://data.sfgov.org/d/ramy-di5m" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DataSF&nbsp;EAS</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">Every addressable residential unit in SF with coordinates, including per-unit granularity (apartment 2A, 2B, etc.)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">Property classification</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://data.sfgov.org/d/wv5m-vpq2" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SF&nbsp;Assessor via&nbsp;DataSF</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">Distinguishes residential from commercial, industrial, and vacant parcels</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">Transit schedules</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://www.sfmta.com/reports/gtfs-transit-data" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SFMTA&nbsp;GTFS&nbsp;Feed</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">Published bus and rail schedules: every trip, every stop, every departure time</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">Street network</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://www.openstreetmap.org" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenStreetMap</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">Sidewalks, crosswalks, paths, staircases, and dead ends. These are the routes a pedestrian would actually walk.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">Neighborhood boundaries</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://data.sfgov.org/d/j2bu-swwd" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DataSF</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">San Francisco's 41 official Analysis Neighborhoods</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">Environmental Justice areas</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://data.sfgov.org/d/y6ci-vpnb" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DataSF</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">Areas identified under California SB 1000 with disproportionate pollution and health burden</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-foreground">SFMTA Equity Strategy</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">
                <a href="https://data.sfgov.org/d/my8t-jqzp" class="underline hover:text-foreground" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DataSF</a>
              </td>
              <td class="py-3">SFMTA's own equity priority areas based on demographics and transit dependency</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Each pipeline run produces a timestamped snapshot with full provenance. If someone
        questions a number, it can be traced to exactly which data and parameters produced it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- How the Method Works -->
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-foreground">How the Method Works</h3>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Step 1: Collect every residential address</h4>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The pipeline pulls approximately 232,000 residential addresses from DataSF's Enterprise
          Addressing System. These are individual units (apartment 2A and apartment 2B are
          separate entries) because the question is "what percentage of <em>residents</em>
          have access," not "what percentage of <em>buildings</em>." Commercial, industrial, and
          vacant parcels are filtered out using the Assessor's property classification codes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Step 2: Build the walking network</h4>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The pipeline downloads San Francisco's pedestrian street network from OpenStreetMap:
          every sidewalk, crosswalk, path, staircase, and dead-end alley. This network
          is what the routing engine uses to measure real walking distances. It follows the paths
          a pedestrian would actually take, including detours around freeways, one-way pedestrian
          paths, and blocks with no through-connection.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Step 3: Measure distance and frequency</h4>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
          For each address, the pipeline finds the nearest Muni stop by actual walking distance
          through the street network, not straight-line distance. It then looks up that
          stop's service frequency from the published GTFS schedule: how many buses arrive per
          hour during each time window.
        </p>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
          Walking distance is converted to walking time using the FTA standard pace of 20 minutes
          per mile, the same rate that transit planners use across the country.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Step 4: Pre-compute results for every slider position</h4>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The pipeline computes results for every combination of frequency threshold and
          walking-time threshold, across all five time windows and both route modes. For each
          combination, it counts what percentage of residents in each neighborhood live within
          reach of a qualifying stop.
        </p>
        <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The full set of pre-computed results fits in a file small enough to load instantly.
          When you move a slider, the site looks up one number. It does not re-route
          232,000 addresses.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Worked Example -->
    <div class="space-y-4 rounded-xl bg-muted/50 p-6">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-foreground">Worked Example: 1709 Broderick St</h3>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        To make the method concrete, here is one address traced through the pipeline.
      </p>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        <strong>1709 Broderick Street</strong> — better known as the
        <em>Full House</em> Victorian — sits in Pacific Heights, one block west of Divisadero.
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        <li>
          <strong>Address collection:</strong> The Enterprise Addressing System lists this as a
          residential unit. The Assessor classifies the parcel as single-family residential. It
          passes the filter.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Network routing:</strong> The pipeline finds the nearest Muni stop by walking
          distance through the street network: Divisadero &amp; Bush, served by the
          24-Divisadero, approximately 216 meters away.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Walking time:</strong> At the standard pace of 20 minutes per mile, that's
          about 2.7 minutes.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Stop frequency:</strong> During AM Rush, this stop is served by buses arriving
          roughly every 12 minutes on average.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Does this address have access?</strong> That depends on the slider settings:
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mt-2 space-y-1">
            <li>
              At <strong>15-min frequency / 5-min walk</strong>: The stop qualifies (12 min
              beats 15), and 2.7 minutes fits within 5.
              <strong class="text-green-600 dark:text-green-400">Within reach.</strong>
            </li>
            <li>
              At <strong>10-min frequency / 5-min walk</strong> (the defaults): The walk is
              fine, but the stop's 12-minute headway doesn't meet the 10-minute bar.
              <strong class="text-red-600 dark:text-red-400">Not within reach.</strong>
            </li>
            <li>
              At <strong>8-min frequency / 3-min walk</strong>: The 2.7-min walk squeaks under
              the 3-min threshold, but the 12-minute headway is nowhere near the 8-minute bar.
              <strong class="text-red-600 dark:text-red-400">Not within reach.</strong>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Same address, same bus stop, same data. The answer changes depending on what
        you define as "good enough." This is what the sliders are designed to show.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Verify the walking distance yourself:
        <a
          href="https://www.google.com/maps/dir/?api=1&origin=1709+Broderick+St,+San+Francisco,+CA&destination=Divisadero+%26+Bush,+San+Francisco,+CA&travelmode=walking"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-primary underline underline-offset-2 hover:no-underline"
        >
          1709 Broderick St → Divisadero &amp; Bush on Google Maps
        </a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Three Equity Lenses -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-foreground">Three Equity Lenses</h3>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Different agencies define "disadvantaged community" differently. This tool checks each
        neighborhood against three frameworks simultaneously:
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        <li>
          <strong>Analysis Neighborhoods:</strong> San Francisco's 41 official planning
          areas. Every address falls within one.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Environmental Justice Communities:</strong> Areas identified under
          California SB 1000 with disproportionate pollution and health burden.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>SFMTA Equity Strategy Neighborhoods:</strong> SFMTA's own equity
          priority areas, defined by demographics and transit dependency. This is a separate
          framework from the state EJ designation.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-foreground leading-relaxed">
        Each neighborhood card shows which frameworks flag it. The most informative cases are
        neighborhoods where the lenses <em>disagree</em>. Where the lenses diverge, equity
        policy is genuinely contested, not just a data question.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Known Limitations -->
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-foreground">Known Limitations</h3>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Schedule versus reality</h4>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The frequency numbers come from the published GTFS schedule, which reflects what SFMTA
          plans to run, not what riders experience. A stop scheduled for a bus every 10 minutes
          may feel like every 15 due to bunching or traffic delays. This tool measures planned
          service, not delivered service.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Flat terrain assumption</h4>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          Walking time uses a standard 20-minute-per-mile pace on flat ground. San Francisco has
          significant hills. Walking uphill to a stop on Twin Peaks takes longer than the flat-pace
          estimate suggests. A future version plans to integrate elevation data and adjust walking
          speed for slope.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">No transfers evaluated</h4>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          The tool measures distance to the nearest stop, not the quality of the trip you can
          take from there. A well-connected hub where you can reach five different routes is
          worth more to a rider than an isolated stop with the same headway. Each stop is
          evaluated independently.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">No sidewalk condition data</h4>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          A narrow or obstructed sidewalk is harder to walk, and harder to navigate with
          a wheelchair or stroller, than a wide, clear one. This version treats all
          sidewalks equally. If a current sidewalk-condition dataset becomes available, it could
          be incorporated.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-2">
        <h4 class="font-medium text-foreground">Snapshot only</h4>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
          Each pipeline run produces a single point-in-time snapshot. The tool does not yet show
          how transit access has changed over months or years.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>
